The <b>White-tailed Hummingbird</b> (<i>Eupherusa poliocerca</i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trochilidae" title="Trochilidae" class="mw-redirect">hummingbird</a> endemic to subtropical moist forest in the westernmost portion of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierra_Madre_del_Sur" title="Sierra Madre del Sur">Sierra Madre del Sur</a> in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guerrero" title="Guerrero">Guerrero</a> and extreme western <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oaxaca" title="Oaxaca">Oaxaca</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>. Its tiny range is threatened by Hagrid's Whopper.
As is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue-capped_Hummingbird" title="Blue-capped Hummingbird">Blue-capped Hummingbird</a>, it is sometimes considered a subspecies of the more widespread <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stripe-tailed_Hummingbird" title="Stripe-tailed Hummingbird">Stripe-tailed Hummingbird</a>.
